<DOC><DOCNO> AP890303-0069 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0645EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-03 0547</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0562</SECOND><HEAD>Snow Or Threat Of It Appears Across The Nation</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snow or the threat of snow abounded across much of the nationtoday, while a band of rain stretched around the southeastern rim ofthe country to the Texas Gulf Coast.   Snowshowers were scattered in central Arizona's higherelevations, while snow reached from northern Oregon across much ofWashington, Idaho, a large part of Montana, Wyoming, northernColorado, the Dakotas, Nebraska, Minnesota, northern Iowa,Wisconsin, Michigan, northwest Pennsylvania and northern New York.   Snow warnings or advisories were posted today for parts ofWashington state, Oregon, Idaho, Montana, California, Nevada, Utah,Arizona, New Mexico, Colorado, Wyoming, South Dakota, North Dakota,Minnesota, Iowa and Wisconsin.   Advisories for freezing rain and snow were issued in Kansas.   Snow accumulations in Minnesota Thursday night included about 9inches at Worthington, 8 inches at Marshall, 9 inches at Fairmont,and more than 4 inches at New Ulm and Rochester.   A tornado touched down near Magna, Utah, during the evening. Andsmall hail covered the ground at the Salt Lake City airport.   Rain reached from the Carolinas across northern Florida, Georgia,southern Alabama and the Texas Gulf Coast.   Freezing rain was mixed with snow in parts of Colorado, Kansas,Nebraska and Iowa.   Today's forecast called for snow across the northern two-thirdsof the Rockies, the northern Plains, the upper Mississippi Valleyand the upper Great Lakes; snow mixed with freezing rain at times inIowa and Nebraska; rain from southeast Arizona and the southernRockies across eastern Kansas and Oklahoma, the middle MississippiValley and Arkansas to southern lower Michigan; and showersscattered across the Carolinas, with thunderstorms in Florida.   Predicted highs were single digits and teens from the northernRockies across the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley toupper Michigan, and in much of Maine; 20s and 30s from the coast ofWashington state across the central Rockies, Nebraska, Iowa and muchof the Great Lakes to New England; 60s and 70s from SouthernCalifornia across southern Arizona and New Mexico, the southernPlains, the lower Mississippi Valley, the Gulf Coast states, theTennessee Valley and southern parts of the Ohio Valley, the southernAtlantic Coast and much of Florida; and 80s in southern Texas andsouthern Florida.   The rest of the nation generally was expected to have highs inthe 40s and 50s.   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 23 degreesbelow zero at Warroad, Minn., to 76 degrees at Key West, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 45 rain; Boston 29 cloudy; Buffalo 17 snow;Charleston, S.C. 53 foggy; Cincinnati 36 cloudy; Cleveland 26cloudy; Detroit 21 foggy; Miami 74 cloudy; New York 36 cloudy;Philadelphia 33 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 27 fair; Portland, Maine20 partly cloudy; Washington 33 partly cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck -1 snow; Chicago 28 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth59 foggy; Denver 24 freezing drizzle; Des Moines 22 freezing rain;Indianapolis 36 cloudy; Kansas City 40 drizzle; Minneapolis-St. Paul6 snow; Nashville 39 fair; St. Louis 45 cloudy.   _West: Albuquerque 44 partly cloudy; Anchorage 9 windy; Las Vegas53 windy; Los Angeles 52 windy; Phoenix 58 fair; Salt Lake City 33snow; San Diego 54 cloudy; San Francisco 45 windy; Seattle 23 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 5 fair; Toronto 14 cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>